    },
    {
      "id": "b484e23bb89cdb05de419941adca13c8e186bf3c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-19 00:28:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nWhile I have nothig against the patch, I wonder how does this help? I suspect if ther eare a lot of accesses to small files the cache would still be filled, is not it?\n\nIs this just in hopes that there are not so much files?\nWhy 8M size, I can imagine a case where a file is a binary to be executed (or a lib) from a lot of nodes and it would better be cached. And I have seen plenty of big binaries.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "19be1992cc8f0d0bc251f0bc9294fd38e89ff989",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-19 01:53:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHmm, I choose 8M, just hope it can alleviate the memory pressure to some extent. I am not sure how to get the \"correct\" cache size in universe, and I guess it would be case by case? Probably the sysadmins should tune it to some value for their sites? Another reason is that DDN, who reported this bug, said that the size of most files on the customer site (met this problem) are around 10M. so I choose a size < 10M to release the OSS pressure. \n\nBut if you suggest we should increase the default cache_size, I am totally fine with that, unless it is 0xffffffff as right now.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "35f95796754d6df3d9e320ba86ee85a7a30254b6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-19 02:01:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI don't have a good number myself, but going by juts one customer is probably bad too.\nLet's see if Andreas has nay ideas.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ee1cda1c64009557a0d4cc0b55f6d6244af8c98c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-19 02:01:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI don't have a good number myself, but going by juts one customer is probably bad too.\nLet's see if Andreas has nay ideas.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "5b4ed8fd6a83ffc2e7c87d3bea6da0f627f09580",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-19 02:01:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI don't have a good number myself, but going by juts one customer is probably bad too.\nLet's see if Andreas has nay ideas.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "630350917858757fb35b5bd8e856e4eae080f359",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-19 07:16:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nI'm OK with the idea of this patch, though I agree it is impossible to get the right size for all customers, but I think this is likely to help in many cases.  I wouldn't mind removing the old comments, but it is not a blocker.\n\n\nIt would probably be better to keep some kind of \"hit count\" on the inode to help decide whether the pages are going to be re-used, even for large files.  One possibility is every time a client needs to read e.g. page index 0 from a file the in-memory inode use count is increased, and at some use count threshold even a large file is kept in cache.  If many clients are reading the same large file the use count would go up quickly and it would be kept in RAM.  \n\nBy keeping the use count in the in-memory inode, there would be some automatic \"use count aging\" as the inodes were evicted from cache.  The next accesses to this file would be uncached unless there are again many clients accessing the file.\n\nThat is work for a separate patch.  I think this should go in for 2.1 so that we can determine if it is helping performance, and whether we need to change the default size value.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
